                <head>346. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On October 4, the Soviet Union launched the world’s first orbiting earth
                    satellite, designated “Sputnik I.” The satellite weighed 184 pounds, or eight
                    times as much as the proposed United States satellite, and orbited the earth
                    once every 88 minutes. Radio signals from the Soviet satellite were picked up by
                    United States Navy tracking stations within moments after Sputnik reached orbit.
                    The Soviet Government announced the achievement the same day.</p>
            </div>
